In libc++, they're constexpr functions that are just 0 and UINT32_MAX, so this is free. If you're using a C++ implementation that doesn't do this, you should find yourself a better implementation. You could just do this instead, though:

  #if defined(__BIONIC__)
  struct Arc4RandomGenerator {
    typedef uint32_t result_type;
    uint32_t min() { return 0; }
    uint32_t max() { return UINT32_MAX; }
    uint32_t operator() { return arc4random(); }
  };

  using RNG = Arc4RandomGenerator;
  #else
  using RNG = std::random_device;
  #endif

The non-bionic case is purely for testing, right? std::random_device as used here is going to open and close /dev/urandom for every single requested random number.

